metadata.name: Plottable Memories: Train Station #65
metadata.description:
'Memories: Train Station' explores plottable abstract photography composition around the "Train Station" theme. Memories can be blurry, faded and abstract and the strokes texturing aim to reflect that.

Many images are used as primitive to make the plot texture. The work is very generative and have great range of variety thanks to the many effects combined together. Photos has been taken by @greweb in Paris' "Gare de l'Est" train station.

Traits of the art includes a suggested "Title" that is self-generated.

PLOTTABLE?!

A SVG file can be exported (right click save) to plot the piece physically. The plot is made of up to 200 000 points – making it time consuming to produce. It is recommended to optimize the pen travel. Inks can have surprising outcomes when done physically.

The digital NFT is the recipe to a plottable art piece, owning it confers the right to plot or request a physical plot from @greweb (https://greweb.me/plots/nft). @greweb would use fountain pens but other plotting artists are free to achieve it with their own materials and ship to collectors – as long as NFT is owned at request time.

More details and Source code: https://github.com/gre/gre/tree/master/doodles/plottable-memories-train-station

metadata.name: Antigravity #276
metadata.description:
To change size or quality, open the IPFS link in a separate window and append to its url a string like `&quality=400&tiles=9,16`. You may notice two parameters in it: `quality` and `tiles`.

`quality` is an integer from 1 to ~1000, the better the quality — the slower the rendering. Default is 200.

`tiles` is a number of 256×256 px tiles to render. Can be an integer (for square images) or two integers separated with a comma (for rectangular). `tiles=9,16` will make an image with width of 9×256 px = 2304 px and height of 16×256 px = 4096 px. If not set, adapts to screen size.

Press `s` to save the image.

metadata.name: Kintsugi #193
metadata.description:
Kintsugi is a philosophy, it's the concept of highlighting imperfections, visualizing patches and seams on the area to focus on, rather than focusing on missing details.

This art of precious scars is a technique used as a means of analyzing the idea of ​​loss through synthesis and restoration of the destroyed and a metaphor for the possibility of rebirth.
Recovery from destructive events is possible through care and patching, not through hiding the damage, but by accepting a new state of the object or the whole life.
The world is a vase that is endlessly disassembled and sewn together again, continuing to bear traces of each event.

Non-human entities helped us put these vases together. In the beginning, there were vague forms, these were the shards themselves, created in collaboration with Latent Diffusion. Over time, they have grown in detail, drawing their stories more clearly, thanks to Jax Diffusion.

The code that puts everything together was written by Yulikolay, for which he is greatly appreciated.

metadata.name: Paper screen door | 明かり障子 (akarishouji) #94
metadata.description:
In a traditional Japanese home, you have sliding walls to separate rooms and create privacy. These are made of wood and washi paper and philtre the light from the sun or moon. 

This is exactly the atmosphere I wanted to convey in this minimalist project. The light of the moon or night lighting plays with the layers of paper in their geometric arrangement. 

The white line represents the part of the wood you touch to open or close the wall. 

Press "Enter" to save the iteration. 

In my usual work, I take everyday objects, materials, etc. and play with them. For this series, I inserted texture of polystyrene.

All graphical elements, colours, and random arrangements were created by code using P5.js, texture patterns are embedded in the code. 

6 colours available : red, yellow, green, blue, white, pink.

@Yomu Oyashi August 2022

metadata.name: Collage #81
metadata.description:
Inspired by traditional Japanese wagami design. We use the iconic patterns of our previous projects to recreate this artwork. All the patterns are generated first and then used to build the scene. 

In this project Aluan brings his delicate texture from his 'Chaos' series, Jinyao brings his beloved pattern from the 'Cloud' series and Wen brings his iconic pattern from the 'Maze'. 'Collage' is not just about mixing our style, but it is also about finding harmony among all the elements. 'Collage' is also about working together, in that we can create something that's difficult to achieve or imagine if we were working alone.

Each piece contains the patterns of all the 3 artists, each artist has a certain number of patterns with different colors. Depending which artist you get, his pattern will be shown as the primary color theme while the pattern of the other 2 artists turns into grayscale to make the primary pattern with color stand out. 

There are 7 different scenes included in this project, which are : Mountains, Waves, Lake, Hexagons, Tetrapods, Chrysanthemums and Lotus. We took great inspiration from the traditional Japanese design, and we discovered these are some of the most common elements in it. Therefore we decide to use them and reimagine them by mixing our patterns. 

The title 'Collage' doesn't only apply to the visual style, but also to the code as well. In this project we mixed p5.js and Vanilla JS. While Aluan and Jinyao work with their patterns in p5. Wen gathered the patterns and recreated the full scene in Vanilla JS.

metadata.name: QuadTubes - Abstract Variations #92
metadata.description:
This piece features abstract patterns created using an algorithm I call QuadTubes.

It works by continuously stroking a set of quadratic curves that run through a set of points while rotating those points along a constant orbit.

This piece features 13 different arrangements and 11 different colors sets, so there should be around 20 pieces of each arrangement. Check the variations function to preview the different arrangements and styles.

The piece will slowly render and automatically pause after reaching its final form. You can press Space to Pause/Unpause the piece and let it run longer resulting in more saturated colors.

You can adjust the rendering speed with up/down-arrows or you can also load the page with
'&Speed=*'
at the end of the url to adjust the rendering speed (default = 25) and press S at any time to save an image of any state of the animation.
 
Initial minters will receive 10% royalties.


PLEASE NOTE: 
This piece was developed in and is best viewed in Chrome (100.0.4896.127). Moreover hardware acceleration needs to be enabled in the browser settings. There are still some browsers & devices that struggle with this piece, most notably iOS and Firefox. There is a fallback which is enabled in Firefox and iOS by default that works without hardware acceleration but produces notably different results in texture and color saturation (especially on iOS). You may force the fallback by appending "&noHA=true" to the url in live view and force the original rendering by appending "&forceHA=true" (Note you can combine multiple URL parameters with an "&", eg "www.fxhash.xyz[...]?Speed=50&forceHA=true").
 Please make sure that you have a device and browser capable of rendering this piece before minting.

metadata.name: Bustling Bright #22
metadata.description:
'Bustling Bright' is a generative drawing on the conpect of the nature of flowers, light, and ground, in an planer and abstract art style. I explore different geometric layouts to mimic variants of plants structures in the nature environment of my garden, full of youth and vitality. The representation of ground is aggregated by group of polygons, filled with smooth and chaotic textures.

This work is also an exploration of generative art in its deterministic structures and stochastic variants. I try to use minimal factors to construct a rich, varied and meaningful results. The constrints and combinations between parameters/factors are deterministic parts of the generative art and the emergence of variety in the complex generation process is its stochastic and unpredictable soul. The deterministic structure provides a stable state of the generative process, but the stochastic parts give the most interesting and unique feelings of the artwork. So what is a generative artwortk? In my opinion, the genrative artwork is not about any one piece of generated result. The Generative artwork is about the total generative space, which represents its all structures and varieties. The creation process of a generative art is not about the author, but also with all its collectors in minting. Because this is a samling process of the generative space, and it is the only way for our human to feel and understand this high dimensional generative space.

I hope you like this work and enjoy the whole nature in its beauty.

Variables:
- 7 strucure pattern
- 17 color palette
- 2 layout

Please be patient with drawing process.

metadata.name: Confini #193
metadata.description:
This is my last fxhash piece for a while, so that I can focus on my personal life. I tried to make a piece that creates the appearance of shapes scratched into the canvas. There are three carefully selected color palettes. One of them is heavily inspired by "Self-Portrait with Bandaged Ear and Pipe", by Van Gogh. These are heavily contrasting colors that I tried to get to work in coherence. One of the color palettes exists out of flavorful colors and means to spark joy in the viewer (depending on the outcome). The final color palette is one that is meant to evoke nothing but calmness. The colors are meant to remind of nature and serenity. I hope you enjoy my work.

Made in p5.js

By twistie
